import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public int uniqueMorseRepresentations(String[] words) {
    String[] morse = {".-","-...","-.-.","-..",".","..-.","--.","....","..",".---","-.-",".-..","--","-.","---",".--.","--.-",".-.","...","-","..-","...-",".--","-..-","-.--","--.."};
    Set<String> transformations = new HashSet<>();

    for (String word : words) {
        StringBuilder morseCode = new StringBuilder();
        for (char c : word.toCharArray()) {
            morseCode.append(morse[c - 'a']);
        }
        transformations.add(morseCode.toString());
    }

    return transformations.size();
}
```

    We first create a `morse` array which contains the Morse code for each letter of the English alphabet. For each word in the `words` array, we loop through each character and translate it to Morse code using the corresponding index in the `morse` array. We then build the Morse code representation of the word and store it in a hash set (unordered_set, Set, or python set) named `transformations`. Using a set ensures that duplicate Morse code representations are not counted. Finally, we return the size of the transformations set which represents the number of unique Morse code representations.
